Natural Language Processing to Analyse Cryptocurrencies¶

Using the Twitter API and Python to extract tweets related to cryptocurrencies in order to find if there is a correlationship between user's opinion (using NLP) and cryptocurrencies prices.

The steps to follow are:

  • Create a Twitter Developer account
  • Install tweepy
  • Extract tweets
  • Use NLP to analyse the tweet's polarity (sentiment analysis - positive or negative opinion)
  • Extract cryptocurrencies prices
  • Compare polarity with crypto prices
  • Profit?

Authenticate in the Developer platform and call the required libraries¶

Extracting financial data from Yahoo Finance¶

For this we may require to first install the yfinance library called in the previous section. We can install it from the terminal using pip:

$ pip install yfinance

Seems to be an outage due to a JSON error, if that's the case, install instead:pip install yfinance --upgrade --no-cache-dir

# stablishing a period of time to analyse
end = datetime.date.today();
start = end-datetime.timedelta(days=7); # seems like with the basic Twitter Developer accpunt I can only extract tweets from the last 7 days only

# Extracting data from yahoo finance. For this we need to have installed finance (pip install yfinance) 
# https://pypi.org/project/yfinance/
BTC = yf.Ticker('BTC-USD');
BTC_close = BTC.history(start=start, end=end)['Close'];
# BTC_open = BTC.history(start=start, end=end)['Open']
ETH = yf.Ticker('ETH-USD');

figure_1, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize = (15, 8));
figure_1.suptitle('Cryptocurrency Prices')

plt.grid();
plt.minorticks_on();

ax2 = ax1.twinx();
plot2 = ax2.plot(ETH_close, color='r', label='Ethereum');
plt.ylabel('ETH US$', color='r');
legends = plot1+plot2;
labels = [l.get_label() for l in legends]
ax1.legend(legends, labels)
ax2.grid(False)

Extracting tweets of interest¶

For this we need to consider the following:

  • We can use the tweepy.Cursor() method in order to paginate large result sets, or only use the api.search() method to get the tweets of the first page only.
  • Define the query keywords and hashtags, for example:
    • Bitcoin or BTC
    • Ethereum or ETH
    • Cryptocurrencies or crypto
    See query logical operators and query basic search operators.

Preprocessing¶

We are gonna clean up the tweets, as these come with emojis, mentions and other text. For this we need to install a preprocessor as this will make it easier and more generic (instead of defining each emoji utf-8 code or html code). For this we can use the tweet-preprocessor library.

To install the tweet-preprocessor run the following command in terminal:

$ pip install tweet-preprocessor

Processing (NLP)¶

Sentiment Analysis consists in mining text in order to extract the subjective information. Sentiment Analysis uses Natural Language Processing (NLP) to identify the text polarity or text tone (positive, neutral or negative). You can read more about how to clean the data and use NLP in Python here! To analyse the tweet polarity we are gonna use the TextBlob library.

In [3]:
prep.set_options(prep.OPT.URL, prep.OPT.EMOJI, prep.OPT.MENTION) #We won't clean the hashtags as sometimes they refer to some concept that could be positive or negative
polarities = [];
unclean_pol = [];
date_tweet = [];
for date_lim in range(0,7):
    queries = '(BTC OR Bitcoin OR bitcoin OR ETHEREUM OR btc OR #btc OR #BTC OR ETH OR Ethereum OR ethereum OR ETHEREUM OR eth OR #eth OR #ETH) lang:en -is:retweet SINCE:'+str(start+datetime.timedelta(days=date_lim))+' UNTIL:'+str(start+datetime.timedelta(days=date_lim+1)) ;
    # extracting tweets and setting them as extended to see the whole tweet (otherwise they will be trucated at 140 char)
    tweets2 = api.search(queries, lang='en', result_type='popular') #for using the free API cannot retrieve more tha about 15 items per search
    tweets2.sort(key=lambda tweet: tweet.created_at)
    for n, tweet in enumerate(tweets2):
        if 'bot' not in tweet.user.screen_name.lower(): #excluding the user names that could be bot 
            followers = tweet.user.followers_count;
            date_tweet.append(tweet.created_at)
            print(f'{n} | User: {tweet.user.screen_name} | Followers: {followers} | Not cleaned\n{tweet.text}\n')
            print(f'Polarity: {TextBlob(tweet.text).sentiment.polarity} Date: {tweet.created_at}\n');
            unclean_pol.append(TextBlob(tweet.text).sentiment.polarity) #As we are lookinh for tweets per day, we will obtain an average of the polarity of the tweets
            #cleaning the tweet and recalculating the polarity
            cleanTweet = prep.clean(tweet.text);
            polarity = TextBlob(cleanTweet).sentiment.polarity;
            polarities.append(polarity)
            print(f'{n} | Cleaned:\n{cleanTweet}\nPolarity: {polarity} Date: {tweet.created_at}\n');
        else:
            print(f'{n} | Possible Bot!! User: {tweet.user.screen_name} | Followers: {followers} | Not cleaned\n{tweet.text}\n')

import scipy #smoothing the graph
x_new = np.linspace(0, len(date_tweet), 1000)
smooth = scipy.interpolate.make_interp_spline(
    [i for i in range(0, len(date_tweet))],
    polarities,
    k=3,
);
pol_new = smooth(x_new)

#To ensure we don't have outliers after interpolating
for n, p in enumerate(pol_new):
    if p > 1:
        pol_new[n] = 1;
    elif p < -1:
        pol_new[n] = -1;

data2 = list(zip(pol_new,x_new)); #joining the data to create a data frame

df2 = df.set_index('date').resample('8H').fillna('pad');
df_zeros = df2.applymap(lambda x: 0) #this df is only for visualization
influencers = ['elonmusk', 'VitalikButerin', 'michael_saylor', 'mcuban', 'rogerkver', 'SatoshiLite', 'novogratz', 'Sonnenshein']
def get_tweets(user):
    queries = 'from:'+user+ ' (BTC OR Bitcoin OR bitcoin OR ETHEREUM OR btc OR #btc OR #BTC OR ETH OR Ethereum OR ethereum OR ETHEREUM OR eth OR #eth OR #ETH) lang:en -is:retweet';
    tweets = api.search(queries, lang='en', result_type='popular') #for using the free API cannot retrieve more tha about 15 items per search
    tweets.sort(key=lambda tweet: tweet.created_at)
    polarities = [];
    date_tweet = [];
    if len(tweets) > 0:
        for n, tweet in enumerate(tweets):
            #followers = tweet.user.followers_count;
            #print(f'{n} | User: {tweet.user.screen_name} | Followers: {followers} | Not cleaned\n{tweet.full_text}\n')
            #print(f'Polarity: {TextBlob(tweet.full_text).sentiment.polarity} Date: {tweet.created_at}\n');
            cleanTweet = prep.clean(tweet.text);
            polarity = TextBlob(cleanTweet).sentiment.polarity;
            #print(f'{n} | Cleaned:\n{cleanTweet}\nPolarity: {polarity} Date: {tweet.created_at}\n');
            polarities.append(polarity);
            date_tweet.append(tweet.created_at)
        return polarities, date_tweet
    

result = list(map(get_tweets, influencers));
inf_pol = [];
inf_date = [];
for i in range(len(result)):
    if result[i] != None:
        for polarity in result[i][0]:
            inf_pol.append(polarity);
        for dates in result[i][1]:
            inf_date.append(dates);

inf_dates, inf_polarities = (list(t) for t in zip(*sorted(zip(inf_date, inf_pol)))); #https://www.finnrietz.dev/python/advanced-list-sorting/
# we are zipping the lists, giving tuples of (date1, polarity1), (date2, polarity2),... and sorting it by the item 1 (date)
# when sorting it generates a list of tuples. So we unpack it with *
# As we have (date1, polarity1), (date2, polarity2),... sorted tuples, if we zip them we get (date1, date2,...) and (pol1,pol2,...)
# So we are just transformin each of these tuples into a list

fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 8))
axs.plot(inf_dates, inf_polarities, color='r', label='Influencers tweets polarity');
axs.grid();
plt.xticks(rotation=45);
axs.minorticks_on();
axs.grid(b=True, which='minor', color='#999999', linestyle='-', alpha=0.2);
plt.ylabel('Polarity');
plt.xlabel('Date [YYYY-MM-DD]');

pl = df2.plot(ax=axs,figsize=(15, 8), linewidth=2, color='b', legend=False);
axs.legend(['Influencers tweets\' polarity','Tweets']);
df_zeros.plot(ax=pl,color='k', legend=False);
axs.plot(inf_dates, list(0 for i in range(len(inf_dates))), color='k', linewidth=2);
